<BaseLayout
  title="The Canon — Christian or Demonic? | Nazaryah"
  description="Who gave you the New Testament? The book in your lap was not handed down from the mountain. It was handed to you by the very system Scripture commands you to come out of."
>
  <article class="cod-article">
    <div class="cod-article-inner">
      <a href="/" class="cod-back"><span class="arrow">←</span><span>Back to Home</span></a>

      <header class="cod-title-block">
        <p class="cod-chapter-label">Chapter Three · Christian or Demonic?</p>
        <h1 class="cod-title">The Canon</h1>
        <p class="cod-subtitle">Who Gave You the New Testament?</p>
        <p class="cod-tagline">Show me where Yahuah authorized it. Show me where the Messiah approved it. Show me where the apostles signed off. You cannot.</p>
      </header>

      <p class="cod-pullquote">The book in your lap was not handed down from the mountain. It was handed to you by the very system Scripture commands you to come out of.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Introduction</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Question No One Is Asking</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">You hold a book in your hands and you call it the Word of Yahuah. You have been told it contains 66 books — 39 in the Old Testament and 27 in the New. You have been told these are the right books, the complete books, the inspired books. You have been told this so often, and from so young an age, that the question never occurs to you.</p>
      <p class="cod-body"><strong>Who decided?</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">Who, exactly, looked at the pile of writings floating around the ancient world — gospels, letters, apocalypses, acts, visions, sermons — and drew a line? Who said, "These twenty-seven are Scripture. The rest are not." Who had the authority to do that? Where is the verse in your Bible that authorizes the man who decided what goes in your Bible?</p>
      <p class="cod-body">You will search in vain. <strong>The verse does not exist.</strong> There is no moment in Scripture where Yahuah authorizes a New Testament. There is no moment where Yahushua commissions the collecting of one. There is no moment where the apostles ratify a list. The idea that the 27 books in the back half of your Bible were divinely assembled and handed down by the Most High is a story you were told — not a story Scripture tells.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The truth is uglier, and it goes by a name most believers have never heard spoken out loud: Athanasius. Damasus. Hippo. Carthage. Constantine. Nicaea. The men who actually gave you the New Testament are the men Scripture warns you to examine with suspicion — and the religion they served is the one you were told you had escaped.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part One</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Old Has a Stamp. The New Does Not.</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">Start with what is solid. The Old Testament — the Tanakh, the Law and the Prophets and the Writings — has a chain of custody Yahuah Himself authorized. He gave the Torah directly to Mosheh on Sinai. He spoke through named prophets whose words were preserved, sealed, and placed beside the Ark (Deuteronomy 31:26). He commanded kings to copy the Law with their own hands (Deuteronomy 17:18). Yahushua Himself confirmed the three divisions of the Hebrew Scriptures when He said, "All things must be fulfilled which were written in the Law of Mosheh, and in the Prophets, and in the Psalms, concerning Me" (Luke 24:44).</p>
      <p class="cod-body">That is a stamp. That is a chain of custody. <strong>The Old Testament has Yahuah's fingerprints on its authorization from the first page.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">Now try to find the same thing for the New Testament. You will not. There is no command from Yahushua to assemble a second collection of Scripture. There is no promise from the Father to inspire one. The writers of the New Testament books <em>did not know they were writing "the New Testament."</em> Paul wrote letters to specific churches about specific problems. Luke wrote a historical account to one man named Theophilus. John wrote a vision down on the island of Patmos. None of these writers said, "Add this to the Book." None of them even knew there would be a Book.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The apostles did not meet at any council to draw up a list. They did not write one another saying, "Which of these should we canonize?" When Peter, James, and John gathered in Jerusalem in Acts 15, they were deciding whether Gentiles had to be circumcised — not which books would be Scripture. When Paul wrote his final letters to Timothy, he did not say, "We have completed the sacred canon." He told Timothy to study <em>the Scriptures</em> — and every Scripture Paul referred to was the Old Testament, because that is all that existed (2 Timothy 3:15–16).</p>
      <p class="cod-body"><strong>The New Testament, as a collection, has no stamp from Yahuah. No stamp from Yahushua. No stamp from the apostles.</strong> The only stamp it carries is from men who came later — men who had already absorbed the religion of Rome.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Two</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Men Who Actually Gave It to You</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">The 27-book New Testament you own today appears in history for the first time in the Easter letter of one man: <strong>Athanasius, bishop of Alexandria, in the year AD 367.</strong> Not the first century. Not while the apostles were alive. Not within the lifetime of anyone who had walked with Yahushua. Three hundred and thirty years after the resurrection — an Egyptian bishop wrote a pastoral letter to his churches and included a list of what he considered acceptable books.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">That is it. That is the first time the exact 27 books appear together in a single list. A letter from a bishop. No divine voice. No burning bush. No angelic visitation. Just a man with authority in the Roman system, writing down what he had decided.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Three decades later, that list was rubber-stamped by a regional synod at Hippo in 393 and then at Carthage in 397 — both meetings convened in North Africa under bishops operating within the Roman imperial church. The Council of Carthage did not receive a revelation. It received a document. The bishops signed off. And from that moment, the book in your lap began to take its current shape.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">Who were these men? Athanasius was not a neutral scribe recording what Yahuah had handed down. He was a political theologian locked in a decades-long fight over the doctrine of the Trinity — a doctrine not found in Scripture in the form he defended it. He was the primary architect of the Nicene understanding of the Father and Son as "one substance," and he spent his career exiled, restored, and re-exiled depending on which emperor favored him. <strong>The man who handed Christianity its canon was also the man who hardened the Trinity into orthodoxy.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Council of Carthage was not a gathering of apostles. It was a gathering of bishops already operating under Roman Catholic authority, already baptizing infants, already praying to saints, already reckoning Sunday as the day of worship. The same council that signed off on your New Testament also included books in the Old Testament that most Protestants now reject as apocrypha — Tobit, Judith, Wisdom, Sirach, Baruch, 1 and 2 Maccabees. The list you now call "Scripture" came out of a system that could not even agree with itself on which books were in the Old half of the Bible.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">And above all of these men loomed the emperor.</p>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Three</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">Constantine and the Religion of the Sun</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">You cannot talk about the canon without talking about Constantine. The entire structure that produced your New Testament — the councils, the bishops, the imperial backing, the uniform creeds — exists because <strong>one pagan emperor decided to merge the religion of Yahushua with the religion of the sun.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">Constantine was not a believer. He was a political pragmatist who worshipped <em>Sol Invictus</em> — the "Unconquered Sun" — for most of his life. Coins minted during his reign depict Sol Invictus on the reverse alongside his own image. His arch in Rome, still standing today, credits his victories to the sun god. He was baptized only on his deathbed. The man who presided over the first ecumenical council of Christianity — the Council of Nicaea in 325 — was a sun worshipper.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">And he did not come to Christianity looking for truth. He came looking for unity. His empire was fragmenting. Three major religions competed for the loyalty of his citizens: the cult of Sol Invictus, the mysteries of Mithras, and the growing movement of Christians. <strong>Constantine's strategy was not to choose one over the others. His strategy was to merge them.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">That is why the symbols of Mithraism — the halo, the solar disk, the sun's rays around the head of the "saints" — began appearing in Christian art under Constantine. That is why the day of worship shifted from the seventh-day Sabbath Yahuah commanded to the "venerable day of the Sun" — <em>dies solis</em>, Sun-day — by imperial decree in 321. That is why Christmas was fixed on December 25 — the birthday of Sol Invictus, Mithras, and every other dying-and-rising sun god of the ancient world. That is why Easter absorbed the rites of the spring fertility goddess — sunrise services, eggs, rabbits, and all.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">And in the middle of this merger, while the old faith of Yahushua was being systematically absorbed into the religion of the sun, a handful of bishops operating inside that same imperial system sat down and decided which books you would read in the morning.</p>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">That is your canon. That is its origin. That is the chain of custody no one in the modern church wants to examine.</p>

      <details class="cod-deepdive">
        <summary>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-label">
            <span class="cod-deepdive-icon">✦</span>
            <span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-title">Go Deeper — The Books They Threw Out</span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-hint">Shepherd of Hermas, Epistle of Barnabas, the Didache, and more</span>
            </span>
          </span>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-chevron">▾</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="cod-deepdive-body">
          <p class="cod-body">If the men who selected the canon were compromised — and they were — then the books they kept and the books they rejected deserve examination. Because the early believers, the ones who actually lived closest to the apostles, were reading more than just the 27 books that survived the cut.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The Shepherd of Hermas</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">Written in the early second century, the Shepherd of Hermas was one of the most widely read books in the earliest assemblies. It was quoted as Scripture by Irenaeus of Lyons, Clement of Alexandria, and Origen. It was bound with the New Testament in the Codex Sinaiticus — one of the oldest complete Bibles in existence. It calls believers to repentance, holiness, and obedience to the commandments. Athanasius rejected it. Hippo rejected it. Carthage rejected it. Why? <strong>Because it called for obedience to the Law, and the Roman system had already decided the Law was obsolete.</strong></p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The Epistle of Barnabas</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">Also bound into the Codex Sinaiticus alongside the New Testament. Quoted as Scripture by Clement of Alexandria. Listed as disputed-but-used by the fourth-century church. Cut from the final list. Again, a book that called believers to holiness and obedience — and again, rejected by bishops already committed to a law-free gospel.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The Didache — The Teaching of the Twelve</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">A first-century manual of discipleship, written to teach new believers how to walk. It opens with the Two Ways — the Way of Life and the Way of Death — and its instructions line up directly with the commandments of the Torah. It was treated as Scripture by some of the earliest assemblies. It was cut. The reason? It was too Hebraic. Too law-oriented. <strong>Too dangerous to a religion trying to rebrand itself around sun festivals and Gentile cultural norms.</strong></p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">1 Clement</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">A letter from the church at Rome to the church at Corinth, dated around AD 95 — possibly the earliest Christian writing outside the New Testament canon. Considered Scripture in the assemblies of Egypt and Syria for centuries. Also bound into the Codex Alexandrinus. Cut. Why? Because it treats Yahuah and Yahushua as distinct — the Father in heaven, the Son seated at His right hand — in language too plain for the Trinitarian theology the later councils were building.</p>

          <h3 class="cod-subsection">The Book of Jubilees and the Book of Enoch</h3>
          <p class="cod-body">Books quoted directly by the New Testament itself. Jude cites Enoch by name and quotes him as prophecy (Jude 1:14–15). Jubilees was treated as authoritative by the community at Qumran and is still canonical in the Ethiopian Bible today. Both were cut from the Western canon. Both directly contradict the Gentile calendar system, the reckoning of time, and the later Catholic doctrines of angels and the heavenly beings.</p>

          <p class="cod-body">You see the pattern yet? <strong>The books that were cut were, overwhelmingly, books that would have anchored believers to the Torah, to the Hebrew calendar, to the Feasts of Leviticus 23, and to a Father and Son who are two distinct Persons.</strong> The books that were kept were the ones easiest to stretch into the framework a Gentile Roman religion needed to survive. That is not canonization by the Spirit of Yahuah. That is curation by a committee.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="cod-deepdive">
        <summary>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-label">
            <span class="cod-deepdive-icon">✦</span>
            <span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-title">Go Deeper — What Scripture Itself Says About This</span>
              <span class="cod-deepdive-hint">Three passages that apply directly to the men who assembled your Bible</span>
            </span>
          </span>
          <span class="cod-deepdive-chevron">▾</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="cod-deepdive-body">
          <p class="cod-body">The fingerprints of compromise do not stop at the table of contents. Scripture itself contains warnings that apply directly to the men who handed you this book.</p>

          <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
            <p class="cod-scripture-text">You shall not add to the word which I command you, neither shall you diminish it, that you may keep the commandments of Yahuah your Elohim which I command you.</p>
            <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Deuteronomy 4:2</p>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="cod-body">Yahuah's word to Yisra'el was not that men could add books to His revelation later. It was that no one was to add or subtract from what He had given. When councils of men centuries after the resurrection sat down and voted which books to include, they were doing the exact thing Yahuah forbade.</p>

          <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
            <p class="cod-scripture-text">Beware of false prophets, who come to you in sheep's clothing, but inwardly they are ravening wolves. By their fruits you shall know them.</p>
            <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Matthew 7:15–16</p>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="cod-body">The fruit of the men who canonized your Bible is not hard to evaluate. They produced the Trinity. They produced Sunday worship. They produced Christmas and Easter. They produced infant baptism, the priesthood, the veneration of Mary, the communion of saints, the doctrine of purgatory, and a thousand traditions that cannot be found in the Scriptures they themselves handed down. <strong>Their fruit is a religion Yahushua would not recognize.</strong> Their fruit is the thing Revelation calls Mystery Babylon.</p>

          <blockquote class="cod-scripture">
            <p class="cod-scripture-text">Come out of her, my people, that you be not partakers of her sins, and that you receive not of her plagues.</p>
            <p class="cod-scripture-ref">— Revelation 18:4</p>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="cod-body">If Yahuah is calling His people out of her, then the book she handed His people cannot be treated as sacred and untouchable. This does not mean throwing the New Testament away — it means reading it with eyes wide open. It means recognizing that the system which gave you this Book has its fingerprints on every page. It means testing everything. Examining every translation. Questioning every verse that happens to support the very doctrines Rome needed.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <div class="cod-divider">◆</div>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Four</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">So What Now?</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-body">This is where most believers panic. If the canon was assembled by compromised men, does that mean we throw the whole thing out? No. <strong>It means the opposite.</strong> It means we read it the way it was meant to be read — as a collection of writings that testify to Yahushua, measured against the only Scripture Yahushua Himself quoted: the Law, the Prophets, and the Writings.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The New Testament is not useless. It contains the eyewitness testimony of men who walked with the Messiah. It contains the letters of Paul explaining how Gentiles come into the covenant. It contains the Revelation given to Yochanan. Much of it is faithful, powerful, and exactly what Yahuah preserved for His people to read.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">But it is not self-authenticating. It does not float above history. It was handed to you by men in a specific system at a specific time for specific reasons — and where their agenda bent the text, you have every right to look closer. Where they hardened the Trinity into the grammar of translation, question it. Where they softened the Law into obsolescence, test it against what Yahushua actually said. Where they replaced the Hebrew names and feasts with Roman equivalents, restore them.</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The standard is simple. Does this agree with the Torah? Does this line up with what the prophets actually spoke? Does this honor the Father as the one Elohim of Yisra'el and the Son as the Mediator at His right hand? Does it call believers back to obedience — or does it excuse them from it?</p>
      <p class="cod-body"><strong>A New Testament read through the lens of the Old is a blessing. A New Testament elevated above the Old is a trap.</strong> That is exactly the trap the men at Carthage set. And that is the trap most of Christianity has walked into without ever knowing it was there.</p>

      <div class="cod-divider">◆</div>

      <section class="cod-part"><p class="cod-part-label">Part Five</p><h2 class="cod-part-title">The Verdict</h2><div class="cod-part-rule"></div></section>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">Christian or demonic?</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The Old Testament comes with Yahuah's seal, spoken from Sinai, preserved through the prophets, confirmed by the Messiah's own words. The New Testament comes with Athanasius's signature, Damasus's blessing, Carthage's vote, and Constantine's imperial shadow hanging over all of it. <strong>Those are two very different chains of custody.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-body">This does not make the New Testament worthless. It makes it accountable. It means you are not required to accept every verse at face value simply because a council in North Africa said so. It means you are required to test it — against the Law, against the Prophets, against the clear speech of the Messiah Himself — exactly the way the Bereans did when they searched the Scriptures to see whether what Paul preached was so (Acts 17:11).</p>
      <p class="cod-body">The men who gave you this Book were not neutral. The religion they served was the same religion that merged the Sabbath into Sunday, the Passover into Easter, the feasts into festivals of the sun. You cannot trust their fruit and reject their tree. You cannot receive their canon as untouchable and then turn around and come out of Babylon. <strong>She handed you the Book. If you are coming out of her, you have to examine what she handed you.</strong></p>
      <p class="cod-pullquote">The question is no longer whether the canon is in your hands. It is. The question is whether you will read it with their eyes — or with His.</p>

